Findings Results & Analysis Comprehensive evaluation results and key findings from our LLM-as-a-Judge research. 87.3% Average Accuracy 15.2% Position Bias Rate 0.82 Inter-model Agreement 23% Length Bias Impact Key Findings Position Bias Most LLM judges exhibit position bias, showing preference for responses appearing in certain positions. GPT-4 and Claude-3 demonstrate the most stability in this regard. Length Preference Longer responses generally receive higher scores, even when content quality is similar. This bias is particularly pronounced when evaluating creative writing tasks. Self-Enhancement Bias LLM judges tend to give higher scores to content they generated themselves. This self-enhancement bias reaches up to 12% in some models. Consistency When repeatedly evaluating the same content, consistency varies significantly across models. Top-tier models achieve over 90% self-consistency. Performance Comparison Performance comparison chart will be displayed here
(Can integrate Chart.js or Recharts for visualization) Key Insight Our research shows that while LLMs as judges demonstrate impressive capabilities, systematic biases still need to be addressed. We recommend using multi-model voting or human-AI collaboration in practical applications to improve judgment reliability. Detailed Results by Category Detailed breakdown by task category
